# Chapter 1: Advanced TypeScript Fundamentals

## Advanced TypeScript Fundamentals

TypeScriptŌĆÖs type system is one of its most powerful features, enabling developers to write code that is both expressive and type-safe. In this chapter, weŌĆÖll explore advanced type system features that allow you to model complex relationships, build reusable abstractions, and enforce safety at compile time. By mastering these concepts, youŌĆÖll elevate your TypeScript skills and write more maintainable, scalable, and robust code.

---

## Union and Intersection Types: Composing Complex Types

Union and intersection types are foundational for modeling scenarios where data can take multiple forms or where multiple types must coexist.

### Union Types (`|`)
A **union type** represents a value that can be one of several types. This is particularly useful when a variable can hold different kinds of data.

```typescript
type Status = "pending" | "approved" | "rejected";

function processStatus(status: Status) {
  console.log(`Processing status: ${status}`);
}

processStatus("approved"); // Ō£ģ Valid
processStatus("invalid"); // ŌØī Type '"invalid"' is not assignable to type 'Status'.
```

In this example, `Status` is a union of string literals. TypeScript ensures only valid statuses are passed.

### Intersection Types (`&`)
An **intersection type** combines multiple types into one, requiring the value to satisfy all types.

```typescript
type Admin = {
  name: string;
  role: "admin";
};

type Editor = {
  name: string;
  role: "editor";
};

type AdminOrEditor = Admin | Editor;
type AdminAndEditor = Admin & Editor; // ŌØī Error: Type 'Admin' and 'Editor' are disjoint

// Instead, use intersection for extending types:
type NamedUser = { name: string };
type AdminUser = NamedUser & { role: "admin" };
```

Here, `AdminAndEditor` fails because `Admin` and `Editor` have incompatible `role` properties. Instead, we use intersection to extend types safely.

**Practical Use Case:**
```typescript
function getUserRole(user: Admin | Editor) {
  return user.role; // TypeScript knows user has a 'role' property
}
```

---

## Generics: Building Reusable, Type-Safe Abstractions

Generics allow you to write functions, classes, and interfaces that work over a variety of types while maintaining type safety.

### Basic Generics
```typescript
function identity<T>(arg: T): T {
  return arg;
}

let output = identity<string>("Hello"); // output is of type 'string'
output = identity(123); // output is of type 'number'
```

### Generic Constraints
You can constrain generics to ensure they meet certain requirements.

```typescript
interface Lengthwise {
  length: number;
}

function logLength<T extends Lengthwise>(arg: T): void {
  console.log(arg.length);
}

logLength("hello"); // Ō£ģ Valid
logLength([1, 2, 3]); // Ō£ģ Valid
logLength(42); // ŌØī Error: number does not have a 'length' property
```

### Generic Interfaces and Classes
```typescript
interface Result<T, E> {
  data?: T;
  error?: E;
}

function parseJSON(json: string): Result<unknown, Error> {
  try {
    return { data: JSON.parse(json) };
  } catch (error) {
    return { error: new Error("Invalid JSON") };
  }
}
```

**Practical Use Case:**
```typescript
class DataStore<T> {
  private data: T[] = [];

  addItem(item: T): void {
    this.data.push(item);
  }

  getItem(index: number): T | undefined {
    return this.data[index];
  }
}

const numberStore = new DataStore<number>();
numberStore.addItem(10);
```

---

## Type Guards and Narrowing: Enforcing Runtime Safety

Type guards and narrowing help you refine types at runtime, enabling safer and more precise type checking.

### Type Guards with `typeof` and `instanceof`
```typescript
function printId(id: string | number) {
  if (typeof id === "string") {
    console.log(id.toUpperCase()); // Type narrowed to 'string'
  } else {
    console.log(id.toFixed(2)); // Type narrowed to 'number'
  }
}
```

### Custom Type Guards
```typescript
interface Cat {
  meow(): void;
}

interface Dog {
  bark(): void;
}

function isCat(animal: Cat | Dog): animal is Cat {
  return (animal as Cat).meow !== undefined;
}

function makeSound(animal: Cat | Dog) {
  if (isCat(animal)) {
    animal.meow(); // Type narrowed to 'Cat'
  } else {
    animal.bark(); // Type narrowed to 'Dog'
  }
}
```

### Discriminated Unions
```typescript
type Circle = {
  kind: "circle";
  radius: number;
};

type Square = {
  kind: "square";
  sideLength: number;
};

type Shape = Circle | Square;

function calculateArea(shape: Shape) {
  switch (shape.kind) {
    case "circle":
      return Math.PI * shape.radius ** 2;
    case "square":
      return shape.sideLength ** 2;
  }
}
```

**Practical Use Case:**
```typescript
function processInput(input: string | Buffer) {
  if (input instanceof Buffer) {
    console.log(input.toString("utf-8")); // Type narrowed to 'Buffer'
  } else {
    console.log(input.toUpperCase()); // Type narrowed to 'string'
  }
}
```

---

## Mapped and Conditional Types: Dynamic Type Transformations

### Mapped Types
Mapped types allow you to transform existing types dynamically.

```typescript
type Readonly<T> = {
  readonly [P in keyof T]: T[P];
};

type Partial<T> = {
  [P in keyof T]?: T[P];
};

interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

type ReadonlyUser = Readonly<User>;
type PartialUser = Partial<User>;
```

### Conditional Types
Conditional types enable type branching based on conditions.

```typescript
type NonNullable<T> = T extends null | undefined ? never : T;

type Result<T> = T extends { success: true } ? T : never;

function handleResult<T>(result: T): Result<T> {
  if (result && (result as any).success === true) {
    return result as Result<T>;
  }
  throw new Error("Invalid result");
}
```

### Keyof and Index Access Types
```typescript
type Stringify<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]: string;
};

type UserStrings = Stringify<User>;
// { id: string; name: string; email: string }
```

**Practical Use Case:**
```typescript
type Optional<T, K extends keyof T> = Omit<T, K> & Partial<Pick<T, K>>;

type UserWithOptionalEmail = Optional<User, "email">;
// { id: number; name: string; email?: string }
```

---

## Key Takeaways

- **Union and intersection types** allow you to model complex data relationships, ensuring type safety when combining or distinguishing between types.
- **Generics** enable reusable, type-safe abstractions, reducing code duplication and improving maintainability.
- **Type guards, narrowing, mapped, and conditional types** provide advanced tools for dynamic type transformations and runtime safety checks.

