### Strategy Pattern: Type-Safe Algorithms

The **Strategy Pattern** defines a family of algorithms, encapsulates each one, and makes them interchangeable. In TypeScript, we can model this using function types and generics.

#### Example: Sorting Strategies

```typescript
type SortStrategy<T> = (data: T[]) => T[];

class DataSorter<T> {
  private strategy: SortStrategy<T>;

  constructor(strategy: SortStrategy<T>) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  setStrategy(strategy: SortStrategy<T>): void {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  sort(data: T[]): T[] {
    return this.strategy(data);
  }
}

// Define strategies
const ascending: SortStrategy<number> = (arr) => [...arr].sort((a, b) => a - b);
const descending: SortStrategy<number> = (arr) => [...arr].sort((a, b) => b - a);
const custom: SortStrategy<{ id: number }> = (arr) =>
  arr.sort((a, b) => a.id - b.id);

// Usage
const numbers = [5, 2, 8, 1];

const sorter = new DataSorter<number>(ascending);
console.log(sorter.sort(numbers)); // [1, 2, 5, 8]

sorter.setStrategy(descending);
console.log(sorter.sort(numbers)); // [8, 5, 2, 1]
```

> ­¤öü **Extensibility**: New sorting strategies can be added without modifying the `DataSorter` class ŌĆö a perfect example of the **Open/Closed Principle**.

