## 3. Developing Custom Type Definition Files

Sometimes, third-party libraries lack proper type definitions (`@types` packages), or you need to extend existing ones to match your projectŌĆÖs expectations.

### Creating `.d.ts` Declarations

Suppose youŌĆÖre using a library `super-api` that has no types. You can create a `super-api.d.ts` file in your `src` or `types` folder:

```typescript
// types/super-api.d.ts
declare module 'super-api' {
  interface ApiConfig {
    baseUrl: string;
    timeout?: number;
  }

  interface ApiResponse<T> {
    data: T;
    status: number;
    ok: boolean;
  }

  export function createClient(config: ApiConfig): {
    get<T>(path: string): Promise<ApiResponse<T>>;
    post<T>(path: string, body: unknown): Promise<ApiResponse<T>>;
  };
}
```

Now TypeScript will understand `import { createClient } from 'super-api';`.

### Augmenting Existing Types

You can also extend global types. For example, to add a custom method to `Array`:

```typescript
// types/global.d.ts
export {}; // Ensure module context

declare global {
  interface Array<T> {
    last(): T | undefined;
  }
}

Array.prototype.last = function() {
  return this[this.length - 1];
};
```

> **Important**: Avoid modifying prototypes in production code. Prefer utility functions instead.

